│ stop({"edit_points": [[3009, 3014,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure inside            │
│ BoUpSLP::getVectorizedOperand: `assert(TE->isSame(VL) && \"Expected same      │
│ scalars.\")`. This function attempts to find a vectorized operand TreeEntry   │
│ for a given user TreeEntry and operand index by scanning the operand's scalar │
│ list VL and matching edges via UserTreeIndices. The assertion assumes that    │
│ the found TreeEntry (by edge association) always has the same scalars         │
│ order/size as the operand's VL. In the reproducer, SLP constructs bundles of  │
│ PHI nodes with various reorders and reuse masks, and some gather nodes have   │
│ different vector factors due to reuse or partial matching (n=2 bundles). This │
│ can legitimately cause a mismatch between the VL being queried and the        │
│ TreeEntry's Scalars/ReorderIndices/ReuseShuffleIndices, even though an        │
│ EdgeInfo association exists.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows  │
│ multiple attempts to schedule PHI bundles with perfect diamond merges and     │
│ several gather nodes with small sizes (e.g., bundles of n=2 and n=4), and     │
│ reuse and reorder shuffles are being applied. We see entries where operands   │
│ have been reordered, and reuse masks affect vector factor                     │
│ (TreeEntry::getVectorFactor). Later, during cost calculation (`Calculating    │
│ cost for tree of size 6`), the pass calls `getSpillCost`, which uses          │
│ `getVectorizedOperand`. The log ends right after accounting costs for         │
│ bundles, before vectorization, indicating the first transformation point is   │
│ indeed in the cost model querying a vectorized operand. Given the variably    │
│ sized bundles and internal users removed, it is plausible the operand's VL    │
│ differs in size/order from the TE associated via UserTreeIndices.\n\n3. Root  │
│ Cause Analysis:\nThe invariant enforced by the assertion in                   │
│ `getVectorizedOperand`—that the TreeEntry associated via UserTreeIndices must │
│ have the same scalars as the operand VL—is not guaranteed across all cases.   │
│ For PHI/gather nodes with reorders and reuse masks, the TE can represent a    │
│ different formation (e.g., a larger Scalars size due to reuse or a different  │
│ order), while UserTreeIndices still records the edge relationship. In such    │
│ cases, `TE->isSame(VL)` can legitimately be false. The function should treat  │
│ this as \"not vectorized operand for this specific VL\" and return nullptr,   │
│ which will cause the caller (spill/cost calculation) to handle it as a        │
